data.value:
Ursa Major (also known as the Great Bear) is a constellation in the northern sky, and visible throughout the year from most of the northern hemisphere. Within the constellation, the Big Dipper can be found. It’s made up of the tail of the Great Bear, along with the lower torso, creating the ‘bowl’ of the Big Dipper. The Big Dipper is one of the most well-known constellations in the world, and is often used for navigation.
In Roman mythology, Jupiter (king of the gods, known by the Greek name ‘Zeus’) seeks the attention of a young woman named Callisto, a nymph. Jupiters jealous wife, Juno, discovers that Callisto has a son named Arcas and assumes that his father is Jupiter. Juno decides to punish Callisto, and transforms her into a bear so she no longer attracts the attention of Jupiter. Years later, the bear form of Callisto encounters her son Arcas. Arcas nearly kills the bear, who unbeknownst to him is his mother. Jupiter decides to turn Arcas into a bear as well, and puts them both into the sky. Callisto forms Ursa Major, and Arcas is Ursa Minor.
Much like Orion’s Belt, it’s currently theorized by Astronomers that Ursa Major’s stars likely contain exoplanets. In fact, one of the stars (referred to as ‘Chalawan’, Thai for crocodile) is currently being investigated on the possibility of hosting three exoplanets.
